–August 1373":"1302–August 1373","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1331–Female":"1331–Deceased","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1272–1320":"1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","August 1373":"August 1373","1320":"1320","1331":"1331","1373":"1373","1272":"1272","1280":"1280","Amblecote, Stourbridge, Staffordshire, England":"Amblecote, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bramshall, Uttoxeter, Staffordshire, England":"Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chebsey, Staffordshire, England":"Chebsey, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stafford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Stafford (Staffordshire), but occasionally from other places with similar names, such as Stafford House in Ifield (Sussex), possibly East and West Stowford in East Down (Devon), and three minor places in Devon called Stafford, in Dolton, Broadhembury, and Colyton parishes. The places are all named with Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ as the final element, but have different initial elements. The Staffordshire placename has Old English <i>stæth</i> ‘river bank, shore’; Stafford in Colyton (Devon) has Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’; the Sussex placename has Old English <i>stēor</i> ‘steer, bullock’; East and West Stowford (Devon) have Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’; Stafford in Dolton and Stafford in Broadhembury (Devon) may have Old English <i>stæth</i>, <i>stān</i>, or <i>stæf</i>.","Irish (Wexford): variant of   Stocker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocker","meanings":["German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>): topographic name for someone living by a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Stafford was born in 1302, in Bramshall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Stafford, was 31 and his mother, Isabel Stafford, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Stafford. He died in August 1373, in Amblecote, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1302–August 1373":"1302–august 1373","1302–1373":"1302–1373","1331–Female":"1331–Surnud","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1272–1320":"1272–1320","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","August 1373":"aug